<document title="debugging">
<content>

Debugging components for the devtools project are provided by the
gnome-debug package.  The gnome-debug package provides abstracted
access to system debuggers, along with graphical components for
viewing and manipulating these debuggers.

<p> 

gnome-debug can be used outside of the devtools framework.  A
standalone debugging tool, called Dryad, is built using gnome-debug.
See the bottom of this page for more information about Dryad.

<p>

gnome-debug is developed on the gnome cvs server in the
<tt>gnome-debug</tt> module.

<head1>capabilities</head1>

Some of the existing components available with gnome-debug are:
<ul>
<li>Breakpoint management (setting/removing, enabling/disabling).
<li>Stack browsing (viewing and changing frames).
<li>Execution (running, stepping, etc).
<li>Variable viewing and manipulation
<li>Register viewing and manipulation
</ul>

<head1>dryad</head1>

Dryad is a standalone debugger build using the gnome-debug components.
Dryad is the testbed for the gnome-debug capabilites, and is useful
for people that don't want a full-fledged IDE but still want a good
graphical debugger.  It is available on the gnome cvs server in the
<tt>dryad</tt> module.

